# docs/DECISION_LOG.md and docs/STATUS.md are append-heavy: two branches
# routinely add different, non-conflicting entries/bullets near the same
# point in the file (e.g. two research-derived decisions both appending
# to the end of DECISION_LOG.md, or two PRs both adding a bullet to the
# same STATUS.md section). Git's default 3-way merge treats any such
# adjacent insertion as a hard conflict requiring manual resolution on
# every rebase -- this session hit it on essentially every stacked PR.
#
# `merge=union` (a built-in Git low-level driver, no external tool
# required) resolves an insertion-only conflict by keeping both sides'
# lines instead of stopping with conflict markers. It does not reorder or
# drop any existing content, and it does not silently resolve a *true*
# same-line edit conflict (there aren't any in an append-only log: old
# entries are never edited per DECISION_LOG.md's own header rule). Worst
# case after a union merge is cosmetic (entries in an unexpected order),
# fixable in the same commit that resolves the rest of the rebase, not a
# correctness risk.
docs/DECISION_LOG.md merge=union
docs/STATUS.md merge=union

